Puzzles solved: That's why we can't tickle ourselves
A kind of brake in the cerebrum prevents people from tickling themselves. Scientists at the Humboldt University in Berlin found this out with the help of experiments on rats, as they announced on Thursday evening. Here, progress has also been made on the question of why children defend themselves so violently against tickling, only to demand more.
Finally, it has also become out why the approaching of a tickling hand triggers laughter even before the touch. This is due to a deep layer in the cerebrum, which already triggers laughter at the expectation of tickling.
According to the data, earlier research showed that rats react with " laughter " in the ultrasound range when tickled by humans. This " laughter " is conveyed by the part of the cerebral cortex that serves the central processing of haptic perception.
Laughing is suppressed during self-touching
So far, it has been assumed that the brain can distinguish between self-touch and touch by others - that is, people cannot tickle themselves. However, the Berlin researchers now found out during the experiments on the rats that the laughter as well as the activity of the respective area of the cerebral cork are suppressed during a self-touch. This is also the case when living beings clean themselves. During the foreign contact and the tickling by the scientists, but the activity in the brain and the impulse to laugh had been intensified.
But if the self-touch and the touch by others pass at the same time, the laughter is also suppressed. This indicates that the brain of the rat could not distinguish between self-touch and the touch by others. The new findings suggested that people cannot tickle themselves because the self-touch activated a brake in the cerebrum.
The rats were also trained to tickle themselves. Thus, they sometimes broke off this initiation in the experiment prematurely, showed escape behavior or rigiof terror. This ambivalence is similar to the behavior of the children. The ambivalence of tickling is a behavioural reaction that is the same in rats and humans.
