Study on heart disease causes
Smoking, obesity, unhealthy nutrition - there are risk factors for cardiovascular diseases. But what really triggers a heart failure or an infarction? Hamburg-based researchers now want to take a close look at the genetic material of 9,000 healthy and sick people.
Through the analysis of the genetic material of 9,000 people, Hamburg and Swiss scientists want to track down the causes of cardiovascular diseases in more detail.
The research project is the largest of its kind in the German-speaking world, the University Hospital Hamburg-Eppendorf (UKE) announced on Friday. The Kühne Foundation is funding the project with 12.5 million euros. From Switzerland, the High Mountain Hospital Davos, which belongs to the Foundation, and the University Hospital of Zurich are involved.
Overweight, smoking and unhealthy nutrition are among the main controllable risk factors for cardiovascular diseases. Genetic factors determine the risk. However, the interaction between genes and external influences is only insufficiently known, it was said. Now the scientists want to compare the complete genome of 8000 healthy people with that of 1000 former patients of the University Cardiovascular Center at the UKE.
Currently, in more than 4000 of the approximately 20,000 relevant human genes, possible disease-causing changes in DNA - so-called mutations - are known, it was said by the clinic. Every year, about 200 were added.
According to the initiators, the aim of the five-year project is to develop new options, such as for the prevention, detection and treatment of cardiac arrhythmias, heart failure and heart attacks. The data could also be used in the study of other common diseases, according to Stefan Blankenberg, head of the University Cardiovascular Centre. New findings on the interaction between heart and brain, heart and kidney as well as on cancer are possible.
The chairman of the Kühne Foundation, Klaus-Michael Kühne (82), also emphasized that there was a firm will to use the data to investigate other diseases. So far, the foundation's clinic in Davos has mainly primarily with allergies. Now a Center for Cardiovasascular Precision Medicine was to be established on the medical incampus and a professorship for bioinformatics would be created. To justify his commitment, the logistics entrepreneur living in Switzerland said that he had been operated at the open heart in Hamburg three years ago and was very grateful.
The organic samples of the healthy participants come from Hamburgers, who also participate in the " Hamburg City Health Study. " According to the hospital ic, this is largest local local health study in the world with 45,000 test persons. In the case of genetic coding, strict attention paid to the protection of the anonymised data data, the scientists insured. It is about one petabyte (1000 terabytes) of data, said Holger Moch from the University Hospital Zurich.
According to the UKE, the genetic material of a human being can be deciphered today within 24 hours. The pure material costs are 1300 euros. The first gene sequencing worldwide, the results of which were published in 2001, has cost several hundred million euros. The study is scheduled to begin on 1 October and all 9,000 samples will be analysed by the end of 2020. Initial results are expected in the following year.
