Attention: NEVER charge smartphone wirelessly
Practical harmful
Inductive technology via Qi standard is extremely practical, but should not be used.
Since several new smartphones have recently been launched on the market that support wireless charging and sell very well - above all the new iPhone 11 models, we would like to recall another study from the beginning of July. The wireless charging of mobile devices is extremely practical, but not necessarily recommended.
Higher temperature sets battery to
Researchers warn against the wireless charging of smartphones. According to the findings of the Univerity of Warwick, this is extremely harmful for the devices. The reason for this is the significantly greater heat generation. If a mobile phone is charged up normally by cable, the battery heats up to 27 degrees within three hours. When charging, on the other hand, the researchers always measured more than 30 degrees on the charging pad, even with the perfect alignment of the smartphone is perfect. If the mobile phone is a little next to the school, the temperature rises even higher. In addition, the wattage strength of the charging pad also increases, which in turn drives the power consumption.
Capacity and Lifetime
According to the researchers, the temperature is a decisive factor for the durability of batteries. Every single degree plays a role. When charging at higher temperatures, the battery not only buron capacity, but it also does not last so long overall. Thus, the service life is lower. The researchers therefore advise to always charge the smartphone by cable. Since a battery exchange with high costs is always associated with modern smartphones, this should be a helpful tip. Apple has recently increased the costs for a battery replacement even again - for all iPhones.

The technology is extremely convenient: simply place the device on a corresponding charging pad - these are now even installed in many restaurants, airports, hotels and cars - and the battery is charged without annoying cable clutter and tedious plug-in fumbling. Since Qi (stands for inductive energy transmission) a worldwide standard prevails, in which exceptionally even Apple participates, there are hardly any restrictions. Nevertheless, according to the researchers, the technology should only be used in exceptional cases.
