Aegean Sea: Baby and four other children drown in boat accident
While capsizing a refugee boat in the Aegean, one baby and four other children drowned. Overall, seven people died in the accident, as the Greek Coast Guard announced on Friday. Nationalities are still unclear.
The boat sank near the Greek island of Inousses, which lies between the island of Chios and the Turkish mainland. Four children, three women and five men were saved.
Hundreds of migrants from Turkey are currently being over to the Greek islands in the east of the Aegean. According to the United Nations Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), 174 people were killed on this route last year. Federal Minister of the Interior Horst Seehofer has now announced his intention to visit both countries.
Together with his French colleague and the responsible EU Commissioner, he wanted to inform himself in Turkey about " the situation situation with the refugee situation, " said Seehofer on Friday. Afterwards, he wanted to learn more about the " administrative problems of the Greeks " in Athens in order to be able to help cope with them.
A spokesperson for the EU Commission confirmed on Friday Seehofer's planned trip with the EU Home Affairs Commissioner Dimitris Avramopoulos and France's Interior Minister Christophe Castaner.
In Greece, an unusually large number of migrants continue to arrive from Turkey. On Tuesday alone, 654 people were transferred to the Greek islands, it was said by the Greek Ministry of Civil Protection on Wednesday.
Is the Turkey deal still working?
The increased figures have recently raised doubts about the functioning of the EU-Turkey agreement concluded in 2016. This provides that the EU can send back all refugees and migrants coming illegally to the Greek islands via Turkey. In return, the EU wanted to take in a Syrian refugee from Turkey for every deported Syrian.
