Influencer wants free upgrade: Lifelong flight ban at Cathay
Allegedly, Jaqueline Ng was promised an upgrade by email from Cathay Pacific. However, when she asked for it at check-in, she was not allowed to be on board - and she should never be allowed to fly with Cathay again.
Spontaneously get an upgrade for Business Class - many passengers dream of that. Sometimes they are lucky, and the check-in staff offer a change from Economy Class for free.
However, this case shows how one should not do it: A self-declared influencer has actively asked the airline Cathay Pacific for a free upgrade. On Instagram, Jaqueline Ng has more than 65,000 users. On May 30, she flew back from Taiwan to New York and on June 7.
On the outbound flight, the employees refused to upgrade Jaquupgrade, although she had shown an e-mail in which Cathay Pacific Pacific allegedly promised her an upgrade. Influencerin wants to receive the letter from an airline marketing employee. However, the airline accuses Jaqueline of falsifying the mail.
On the return flight, Jaqueline again again to get an upgrade for the long-haul flight. This time, the woman is said to have shown the same mail, but with a different reference number. The employees at JFK airport were skeptical: they checked at the head office. And indeed, the employee from whom the mail originated is said to have denied the mail contact with Jaqueline. This also confirmed the mail system, in which the messages did not appear.
The airline staff at the airport canceled Jaquelines Ticket and imposed a lifelong flight ban with Cathay Pacific. For 1,400 US dollars (about 1,280 euros) she had to buy a new flight tick to Taiwan.
With her case, the influencer turned to Elliot Advocacy, a company that represents consumer interests, because Cathay had reimbursed her the price for her original ticket, but Jaqueline also demanded the costs for the new ticket.
But as long as Jaqueline does not submit the metadata of the mail, the case remains clear: the influencer has committed fraud for Cathay and remains blocked for future flights. The airline's terms and conditions also state that it does not have to pay the new flight. Jaqueline does not want to be satisfied with it - and now calls s a lawyer.
Oil prices decline according to ceasefire report in Yemen
Oil prices fell by more than one dollar on Friday afternoon within a very short time. A barrel (159 liters) of the North Sea variety Brent cost 61.83 US dollars - about 1.4 percent less than the day before. The price of a barrel of the American variety West Texas Intermediate (WTI) fell by 1.3 percent to 55.77 dollars.
The slide was triggered by a report by the Wall Street Journal on a ceasefire in Yemen. Saudi Arabia is said to have agreed to a ceasefire in four areas.
A drone attack on the oil plants in Saudi Arabia brought five percent of global oil production to a standstill in mid-September. Houthi rebels allied with Iran in the civil war country of Yemen had claimed the attacks for themselves. Saudi Arabia, like the US government, blames Iran. A ceasefire would defuse the political tension in the region.
If an agreement is actually reached, the focus could be on growth and demand concerns, said Ole Hansen, Head of the Commodity Strategy Division at Saxo Bank of the Bloomberg news agency.
Oil prices are thus continuing its downward movement over the past few days. A week ago, a barrel of WTI oil had cost up nearly $59, Brent nearly $65.
Most recently, Bloomberg had reported, citing insiders, that the repair work on oil plants in Saudi Arabia was progressing faster than expected after the attack in mid-September. Accordingly, the production volume had again reached a volume of eight million barrels per day and moved again in the direction of the original quantity.
Most recently, there have been several press reports citing insiders who report rapid progress by the state-owned oil company Saudi Aramco in repair work. However, raw ty experts pointed out that Saudi Aramco is currently planning an IPO and wants to avoid negative headlines.
At the same time, there was some relaxation ation in the conflict between Iran and Western countries: the British oil oil tanker " Stena Impero " is on its way more than two months after the arrest by Iran and the recently granted release to leave the port. The crew is now preparing for departure while the ship is still at anchor, shipping director Erik Hånell told Swedish radio in a text message on Friday morning.
But the US announced that it would move off missiles and soldiers to Iran's arch-enemy in Saudi Arabia. Fear of an escalation between the Islamic Republic and countries like the US and the United Kingdom had at times driven up oil prices in recent weeks.
