North Korea considers third summit of Trump and Kim to be questionable
North Korea has expressed doubts that a third summit of leader Kim Jong-un and US President Donald Trump will soon be place in the nuclear dispute. The sense and prospects of success of such a meeting are questionable due to a lack of progress in implementing agreements of the first summit in Singapore, top plomat Kim Kye-gwan said on Friday according to the agency KCNA.
The US has so far done nothing to implement the summit's decisions last year, the North Korean State Department adviser said. He also criticized tightened US sanctions and the joint military maneuvers of the US and South Korea. However, he hoped for a " wise " and " courageous " decision by Trump to bring back another rapprochement.
Trump had said on Monday that he wanted to know what a third summit with Kim should bring before he explained it. Negotiations on disarmament of North Korea's nuclear and missile program have stalled since the failed second summit meeting of Trump and Kim in Hanoi in February. In June, both met in the demilitarized zone between the two Korean states. They agreed to revive the consultations, but so far without much success.
